Cut the @cauliflower{1} into bite-sized florets. Cut the @Yukon Gold potatoes{12%ounce} into 1/2-inch pieces. Peel, halve, and thinly slice the @yellow onion{1}. Coarsely chop the @cilantro{1%bunch}. Thinly slice the @chili pepper{1}.

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in #large tall-sided pan{} over medium heat. Add the onion and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook for about ~{5%minutes}, until softened. Add the @coriander{1%teaspoon}, @cumin{1%teaspoon}, @curry powder{1%tablespoon}, and as much Thai chili as you dare. Cook, stirring, for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant.

Add the cauliflower and potatoes and cook, stirring, for another ~{5%minutes} until veggies begin to soften. Season with salt and pepper.

Add 1 cup of water and @crushed tomatoes{1%12oz can} to the pan. Season with salt and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer and cook, covered for about ~{15%minutes}, until potatoes and cauliflower are tender.

> If you need more liquid to cover the cauliflower, add additional crushed tomatoes or water.

Add the @peas{4%ounce} and half the cilantro to the pan and cook for ~{2%minutes} to heat through. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Garnish with remaining cilantro and enjoy!

> India has one of the most creative vegetarian cuisines out there! A large percentage of its population sticks to a vegetarian or vegan diet.

> Leftovers taste even better the next day.